<section xml:id="sec-quadratic_functions" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Quadratic Functions</title>
  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>
	find the vertex of a quadratic function,
      </li>
      <li>
	find the \(x\)-intercept(s) of a quadratic function
      </li>
      <li>
	find the \(y\)-intercept of a quadratic functions,
      </li>
      <li>
	find the line of symmetry of a quadratic functions, and
      </li>
      <li>
	graph a quadratic function.
      </li>
    </objectives>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      In this section, we study a polynomial functions of degree 2.
      These polynomial functions are often called <em>quadratic function</em>.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection>
    <title>Quadratic Functions as Degree Two Polynomials</title>
    <definition xml:id="def-quadratic_function">
      <title>Quadratic Function</title>
      <p>
	A function <m>f \colon \R \to \R</m> is <term>quadratic</term>
	<idx>
	  <h>Function</h>
	  <h>Quadratic</h>
	</idx>
	if it has the form
	<me>f(x) = ax^2 + bx + c
	\quad\text{or}\quad
	y = ax^2 + bx + c,</me>
	where <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m> are numbers, and <m>a \neq 0</m>.
      </p>
    </definition>

  <xi:include href="worksheets/wksht-quadratic_functions.ptx"/>
</section>
